1
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:40,434
[Cheerful music plays, background]

2
00:02:35,120 --> 00:02:37,156
That's a big fella! Whoa!

3
00:02:40,240 --> 00:02:42,629
[Calypso music plays, background]

4
00:02:48,240 --> 00:02:49,832
[Birds chirping]

5
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:06,195
BARBARA: Looks great.
ADAM: Thank you.

6
00:03:06,280 --> 00:03:08,111
Happy vacation, honey.

7
00:03:09,480 --> 00:03:11,994
Manchurian tung oil!
Where did you get this?

8
00:03:12,320 --> 00:03:13,912
Helen got it for me in Oslo.

9
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:17,595
There's enough here
to do the whole table and the bureau.

10
00:03:19,960 --> 00:03:21,791
I wonder what this could be.

11
00:03:21,880 --> 00:03:24,155
Oh, honey, you got it. Thank you.

12
00:03:24,240 --> 00:03:26,356
Enough to do the entire guest room.

13
00:03:26,440 --> 00:03:28,715
I'm so glad we're spending
our vacation at home.

14
00:03:28,800 --> 00:03:31,360
- I'm gonna get started now.
- Where are you going?

15
00:03:31,440 --> 00:03:33,032
[Barbara giggles]

16
00:03:33,320 --> 00:03:34,753
[Phone rings]

17
00:03:35,440 --> 00:03:37,476
- I'll get it.
- Be my guest.

18
00:03:38,360 --> 00:03:39,998
[Barbara giggles]

19
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:44,150
- Maybe you should get it.
- I'll go.

20
00:03:44,840 --> 00:03:46,273
[Both giggle]

21
00:03:46,720 --> 00:03:48,711
[Phone continues to ring]

22
00:03:48,960 --> 00:03:50,188
[Car horn honks]

23
00:03:50,280 --> 00:03:51,474
Oh, no!

24
00:03:57,160 --> 00:03:58,354
BARBARA: Jane.

25
00:04:00,240 --> 00:04:02,071
It's your turn, honey.

26
00:04:12,520 --> 00:04:13,953
[Both giggle]

27
00:04:14,400 --> 00:04:16,436
- Good luck, honey.
- Thanks.

28
00:04:18,560 --> 00:04:21,518
Hi, Barbara. I'm glad I caught you.
Heard you were on vacation.

29
00:04:21,600 --> 00:04:23,033
That's right. Complete vacation.

30
00:04:23,120 --> 00:04:24,838
Today I'm $260,000!

31
00:04:26,840 --> 00:04:29,673
- It's 6:45 in the morning.
- This offer is real.

32
00:04:29,760 --> 00:04:33,036
From a man in New York City
who only saw a photograph.

33
00:04:33,120 --> 00:04:35,759
Jane, don't send people photos
of our house.

34
00:04:35,840 --> 00:04:39,913
He wants to bring the wife and family here
for some peace and quiet.

35
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:41,718
That's what we're looking for.

36
00:04:41,800 --> 00:04:46,032
This house is too big for you.
It ought to be for a couple with kids.

37
00:04:47,760 --> 00:04:50,957
JANE: I didn't mean anything.
But this house is too big.

38
00:04:51,160 --> 00:04:53,355
BARBARA: I'll see you
in a few weeks. Okay?

39
00:04:53,440 --> 00:04:54,953
JANE: Think about it.

40
00:04:58,240 --> 00:05:00,629
[Calypso music plays on tape deck]

41
00:05:06,200 --> 00:05:06,996
Boo!

42
00:05:07,680 --> 00:05:09,875
I was telling Barbara about this offer
on the house...

43
00:05:09,960 --> 00:05:10,949
No, Jane.

44
00:05:17,120 --> 00:05:18,519
[Music stops playing]

45
00:05:18,600 --> 00:05:20,431
Come with me to the store.

46
00:05:20,520 --> 00:05:23,876
BARBARA: What for?
ADAM: I need a new brush for the tung oil.

47
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:26,116
ADAM: And I want to get
a part for the model.

48
00:05:26,200 --> 00:05:27,838
Just run in, okay?

49
00:05:28,160 --> 00:05:30,594
[Light, cheerful music, background]

50
00:05:39,640 --> 00:05:41,073
[Engine revs]

51
00:05:45,600 --> 00:05:48,398
ADAM: Two weeks at home.
The perfect vacation.

52
00:05:48,920 --> 00:05:52,469
BARBARA: Jane says we should sell
the house to someone with a family.

53
00:05:52,560 --> 00:05:55,393
I don't think it's any of Jane's business.

54
00:05:55,920 --> 00:05:58,878
Besides, we could try again
on this vacation.

55
00:05:59,280 --> 00:06:01,271
Really? What are you saying?

56
00:06:17,800 --> 00:06:20,837
ADAM: How are you doing, Ernie?
ERNIE: Hi, how are you?

57
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:30,353
BILL: Good morning, Adam.

58
00:06:30,440 --> 00:06:32,908
- Need a haircut before your vacation?
- No, thanks, Bill.

59
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:34,592
- How's the model coming?
- Great.

60
00:06:34,680 --> 00:06:38,673
You know, Bozman built that foundation
in 1835. His grandson...

61
00:06:39,960 --> 00:06:41,552
[Wind chimes tinkle]

62
00:06:43,640 --> 00:06:46,154
[Bill continues mumbling to himself]

63
00:06:48,680 --> 00:06:51,558
He's got hair down
to his goddamn shoulders.

64
00:06:52,040 --> 00:06:54,713
He says to me, '"Just trim it a little.'"

65
00:06:55,120 --> 00:06:58,271
- I took the scissors to him so fast...
- See you later.

66
00:07:00,560 --> 00:07:01,959
BILL: Right.

67
00:07:03,320 --> 00:07:05,788
[Light, cheerful music, background]

68
00:07:12,080 --> 00:07:15,595
- This will be great.
- Wouldn't you rather go to Jamaica?

69
00:07:16,080 --> 00:07:19,231
- No way. There's no place like home.
- Look out for that...

70
00:07:19,320 --> 00:07:20,673
[Barbara screams]

71
00:07:20,960 --> 00:07:22,109
[Bang]

72
00:07:25,680 --> 00:07:26,874
[Creaking]

73
00:07:27,160 --> 00:07:29,628
[Suspenseful instrumental beat,
background]

74
00:07:35,880 --> 00:07:37,791
[Adam and Barbara scream]

75
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:39,228
[Splash]

76
00:07:40,320 --> 00:07:43,118
[Dramatic instrumental music, background]

77
00:07:51,320 --> 00:07:52,833
[Clock cuckoos]

78
00:07:56,400 --> 00:07:57,833
[Flames roar]

79
00:07:59,560 --> 00:08:01,039
[Door squeaks]

80
00:08:02,440 --> 00:08:04,749
BARBARA: Perfect start to our vacation.

81
00:08:04,840 --> 00:08:07,308
ADAM: You'll feel better when you're dry.

82
00:08:09,200 --> 00:08:11,839
BARBARA: That fire wasn't burning
when we left.

83
00:08:12,880 --> 00:08:16,270
ADAM: How's your arm?
BARBARA: I don't know. It feels frozen.

84
00:08:19,120 --> 00:08:21,509
[Eerie instrumental music, background]

85
00:08:21,600 --> 00:08:22,589
[Explosive sound]

86
00:08:22,680 --> 00:08:24,193
[Barbara gasps]

87
00:08:30,360 --> 00:08:32,635
[Eerie instrumental music, background]

88
00:08:32,720 --> 00:08:35,393
I'll make some coffee
and you get wood for the fire.

89
00:08:35,480 --> 00:08:38,153
Maybe we should take things extra slow.

90
00:08:38,240 --> 00:08:40,913
Do you remember how
we got back up here?

91
00:08:42,760 --> 00:08:46,036
I'm going back to that bridge
and retrace our steps.

92
00:08:52,720 --> 00:08:54,995
[Eerie instrumental vibrations]

93
00:08:59,840 --> 00:09:01,910
ADAM: You saved my...
BARBARA: Two hours!

94
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:05,834
ADAM: You won't believe... What?
BARBARA: That's how long you were gone.

95
00:09:06,480 --> 00:09:09,870
ADAM: What is going on?
BARBARA: I have to show you something.

96
00:09:10,680 --> 00:09:11,874
BARBARA: Look.

97
00:09:19,440 --> 00:09:20,998
BARBARA: There's that.

98
00:09:21,360 --> 00:09:22,998
And there's that.

99
00:09:30,280 --> 00:09:33,431
- '"Handbook for the Recently Diseased.'"
- Deceased.

100
00:09:35,920 --> 00:09:37,194
Deceased.

101
00:09:37,440 --> 00:09:40,910
I don't know where it came from.
Look at the publisher.

102
00:09:41,400 --> 00:09:44,039
[Eerie instrumental music, background]

103
00:09:44,760 --> 00:09:47,593
'"Handbook for
the Recently Deceased Press.'"

104
00:09:48,080 --> 00:09:51,356
You know what?
I don't think we survived the crash.

105
00:09:55,600 --> 00:09:56,953
BARBARA: I hate this.

106
00:09:57,040 --> 00:09:59,110
Can you give me the basics?

107
00:10:00,040 --> 00:10:02,918
This book isn't arranged that way.
What do you want to know?

108
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:06,276
Why did you disappear
when you stepped off the porch?

109
00:10:06,360 --> 00:10:08,794
Are we halfway to heaven
or halfway to hell?

110
00:10:08,880 --> 00:10:10,598
How long will this last?

111
00:10:10,680 --> 00:10:13,069
ADAM: I don't see anything
about heaven or hell.

112
00:10:13,160 --> 00:10:15,799
This book reads like stereo instructions.
Listen.

113
00:10:15,880 --> 00:10:17,757
'"Geographical and Temporal Perimeters.

114
00:10:17,840 --> 00:10:20,957
'"Functional perimeters vary from
manifestation to manifestation.'"

115
00:10:21,040 --> 00:10:22,189
[Bang]

116
00:10:23,040 --> 00:10:24,871
This is going to take some time.

117
00:10:24,960 --> 00:10:26,552
[Barbara groans]

118
00:10:35,840 --> 00:10:37,592
[Betelgeuse humming]

119
00:10:47,520 --> 00:10:50,318
BETELGEUSE: Damn sandworms.
Thirteen percent, huh?

120
00:10:50,560 --> 00:10:53,757
I better find a job.
Let's see. Business section.

121
00:10:59,600 --> 00:11:02,239
BETELGEUSE: What do we got here?
The Maitlands.

122
00:11:04,040 --> 00:11:06,793
Cute couple. Look nice and stupid, too.

123
00:11:08,720 --> 00:11:10,153
[Betelgeuse cackles]

124
00:11:10,240 --> 00:11:12,629
[Calypso music plays, background]

125
00:11:13,600 --> 00:11:16,433
ADAM: I wish I had a better view
of the cemetery from here.

126
00:11:16,520 --> 00:11:19,193
I can't tell which is
the best placement for us.

127
00:11:20,280 --> 00:11:22,271
[Barbara huffs and puffs]

128
00:11:24,400 --> 00:11:25,799
ADAM: Cabin fever?

129
00:11:26,200 --> 00:11:28,077
I can't clean anything properly.

130
00:11:28,160 --> 00:11:30,833
The vacuum's in the garage
and we can't leave the house.

131
00:11:30,920 --> 00:11:34,310
Why don't they tell us something?
Where are the other dead people?

132
00:11:34,400 --> 00:11:36,436
Why is it just you and me?

133
00:11:37,160 --> 00:11:38,957
Maybe this is heaven.

134
00:11:39,640 --> 00:11:42,279
In heaven there wouldn't be dust
on everything.

135
00:11:50,560 --> 00:11:51,879
ADAM: It's Jane.

136
00:11:55,400 --> 00:11:57,152
BARBARA: What's she doing here?
ADAM: I don't know.

137
00:11:57,240 --> 00:11:59,037
Jane, up here. Jane!

138
00:12:05,120 --> 00:12:07,111
She can't see you, right?

139
00:12:09,640 --> 00:12:13,428
In the book, rule number two:
'"The living usually won't see the dead.'"

140
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:17,639
- Won't or can't?
- It just says '"won't.'"

141
00:12:17,720 --> 00:12:21,508
God, this book is so stupid!
I can't understand anything in it.

142
00:12:22,760 --> 00:12:24,239
Barb, honey...

143
00:12:24,920 --> 00:12:26,399
...we're dead.

144
00:12:26,680 --> 00:12:29,877
I don't think we have much
to worry about anymore.

145
00:12:33,240 --> 00:12:35,879
[Eerie instrumental music, background]

146
00:12:49,400 --> 00:12:51,550
[Thunder rumbling, objects rattling]

147
00:12:53,360 --> 00:12:54,952
[Barbara yelps, bang]

148
00:12:57,600 --> 00:12:58,999
[Door slams]

149
00:13:01,320 --> 00:13:04,278
CHARLES: This is great!
Just what the doctor ordered.

150
00:13:06,040 --> 00:13:07,029
[Bang]

151
00:13:10,160 --> 00:13:11,593
Sorry, ma'am.

152
00:13:13,600 --> 00:13:15,636
Delia Deetz, welcome home.

153
00:13:17,040 --> 00:13:18,268
Charles!

154
00:13:18,760 --> 00:13:23,151
It's okay, there's no damage. See?
Good, sturdy, country craftsmanship.

155
00:13:23,680 --> 00:13:27,639
Look at that kitchen.
You'll finally be able to cook a decent meal.

156
00:13:30,400 --> 00:13:32,038
Come and have a look.

157
00:13:36,640 --> 00:13:39,108
[Light, cheerful music, background]

158
00:13:40,720 --> 00:13:43,598
A little gasoline. Blowtorch. No problem.

159
00:13:44,720 --> 00:13:46,631
MOVER: Excuse me. Here we go.

160
00:13:57,440 --> 00:13:59,670
CHARLES: We'll have to rip out
all the plumbing.

161
00:13:59,760 --> 00:14:02,752
Other than that, it's perfect. Just perfect.

162
00:14:03,840 --> 00:14:06,991
CHARLES: What do you think, honey?
LYDIA: Delia hates it.

163
00:14:10,200 --> 00:14:11,599
I could live here.

164
00:14:11,840 --> 00:14:13,432
Careful! That's my sculpture.

165
00:14:13,520 --> 00:14:16,592
I don't mean '"my'" as in '"I bought it.'"
I mean I made it.

166
00:14:18,560 --> 00:14:20,312
Put it on the table.

167
00:14:21,520 --> 00:14:22,430
[Bang]

168
00:14:28,320 --> 00:14:31,278
Ten minutes. I'm already perfectly at ease.

169
00:14:32,160 --> 00:14:33,513
It's perfect.

170
00:14:33,600 --> 00:14:34,715
OTHO: Help!

171
00:14:35,600 --> 00:14:36,919
DELIA: It's Otho.

172
00:14:37,440 --> 00:14:39,874
CHARLES: Otho, why don't you come
in the front door?

173
00:14:39,960 --> 00:14:40,756
[Bang]

174
00:14:40,840 --> 00:14:41,989
OTHO: It's bad luck.

175
00:14:42,080 --> 00:14:44,878
DELIA: You left the city for me.
I am so happy.

176
00:14:45,240 --> 00:14:46,912
Of course you are.

177
00:14:49,480 --> 00:14:51,550
- Let's get one thing straight.
- Right.

178
00:14:51,640 --> 00:14:55,349
We're here to enjoy the country setting,
not to trash the place!

179
00:14:55,440 --> 00:14:58,034
OTHO: Charles, you're lucky
the yuppies are buying condos...

180
00:14:58,120 --> 00:15:02,079
...so you can afford what I'm going
to have to do to this place.

181
00:15:02,360 --> 00:15:06,353
I'm here to relax and clip coupons,
and, damn it, I mean to do it.

182
00:15:06,440 --> 00:15:09,034
Then go do it quietly, dear,
and let Otho and me think.

183
00:15:09,120 --> 00:15:11,315
OTHO: Is the rest of the house
as bad as this?

184
00:15:11,400 --> 00:15:13,197
Is this a punishment?

185
00:15:14,360 --> 00:15:15,998
What are we going to do?

186
00:15:16,840 --> 00:15:19,070
We're not completely helpless.

187
00:15:19,360 --> 00:15:23,672
ADAM: I've been reading that book and
there's a word for people in our situation.

188
00:15:23,920 --> 00:15:25,114
Ghosts!

189
00:15:26,440 --> 00:15:28,749
OTHO: Let's get this show on the road.

190
00:15:31,880 --> 00:15:34,155
We're dealing with
negative entertainment potential.

191
00:15:34,240 --> 00:15:36,959
There's absolutely no organic flow through.

192
00:15:37,040 --> 00:15:39,838
I noticed that, too.
It's like a giant ant farm.

193
00:15:40,840 --> 00:15:42,353
[Floor squeaks]

194
00:15:42,840 --> 00:15:45,229
- What?
- I thought I saw something.

195
00:15:56,240 --> 00:15:58,196
OTHO: You've read my mind.

196
00:15:58,560 --> 00:15:59,276
I did?

197
00:15:59,360 --> 00:16:01,430
OTHO: So few clients are able
to read my mind.

198
00:16:01,520 --> 00:16:03,988
They're not open to the experience.

199
00:16:08,240 --> 00:16:09,434
[Delia gasps]

200
00:16:10,720 --> 00:16:11,709
[Barbara screams]

201
00:16:11,800 --> 00:16:12,994
My God!

202
00:16:13,680 --> 00:16:17,639
We just have to pray the other closets
are bigger than this one.

203
00:16:17,960 --> 00:16:19,075
OTHO: Look!

204
00:16:20,040 --> 00:16:21,712
Ozzie and Harriet.

205
00:16:24,200 --> 00:16:25,872
- What happened to these people?
- They died.

206
00:16:25,960 --> 00:16:27,951
Look, an indoor outhouse.

207
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:36,037
- Viridian.
- Viridian. Why do I know that name?

208
00:16:36,520 --> 00:16:37,873
Blue-green!

209
00:16:38,600 --> 00:16:40,511
OTHO: Hydrated chromic oxide.

210
00:16:40,880 --> 00:16:44,236
Remember, I'm schooled in chemistry.
I was a hair analyst.

211
00:16:44,320 --> 00:16:45,833
- What?
- Briefly.

212
00:16:47,640 --> 00:16:49,119
[Door squeaks]

213
00:16:51,560 --> 00:16:53,596
Deliver me from L.L. Bean.

214
00:16:54,680 --> 00:16:55,829
[All scream]

215
00:16:55,920 --> 00:16:59,390
I know what you two are up to
and you're not going to get away with it!

216
00:16:59,480 --> 00:17:01,038
This is not working out.

217
00:17:01,120 --> 00:17:05,352
DELIA: I will not stop living and breathing
art just because you need to relax.

218
00:17:05,600 --> 00:17:08,114
I'm here with you. I'll live with you
in this hellhole.

219
00:17:08,200 --> 00:17:12,751
But I must express myself. If I can't
gut this house and make it my own...

220
00:17:13,320 --> 00:17:16,278
...I will go insane
and I will take you with me!

221
00:17:18,400 --> 00:17:21,870
Yeah. Well, maybe the house could use
a little remodeling.

222
00:17:21,960 --> 00:17:25,236
But why don't you just leave
this room alone, okay?

223
00:17:26,520 --> 00:17:27,396
Okay.

224
00:17:33,040 --> 00:17:34,393
I'll get her.

225
00:17:35,200 --> 00:17:36,030
So?

226
00:17:36,120 --> 00:17:40,591
Once you cover the wallpaper, knock down
a few walls, this place might be livable.

227
00:17:40,680 --> 00:17:43,353
- What's on the third floor?
- Attic space.

228
00:17:43,440 --> 00:17:45,749
I forgot to lock the attic door.

229
00:17:48,840 --> 00:17:51,308
[Light, cheerful music, background]

230
00:17:53,200 --> 00:17:55,156
- Did you feel something?
- When?

231
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:06,833
- You don't have a key?
- Maybe Charles does.

232
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:11,118
I have a feeling there's something
very interesting behind this door.

233
00:18:11,200 --> 00:18:14,875
Yeah, the ghosts of the people who died
in this house, and they want us out!

234
00:18:14,960 --> 00:18:16,791
Let's do them a favor.

235
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:34,911
ADAM: My God, that was close!

236
00:18:36,720 --> 00:18:38,597
BARBARA: I cannot watch this.

237
00:18:39,120 --> 00:18:42,032
What's the good of being a ghost
if you can't frighten people away?

238
00:18:42,120 --> 00:18:44,634
- Honey?
- No, I'm not putting up with this!

239
00:18:50,240 --> 00:18:51,753
[Barbara gasps]

240
00:18:54,120 --> 00:18:57,476
ADAM: You don't know what's out there.
BARBARA: I don't care.

241
00:18:58,320 --> 00:18:59,878
ADAM: [Yells] Barbara!

242
00:19:00,320 --> 00:19:02,038
[Eerie instrumental music]

243
00:19:03,520 --> 00:19:05,317
BARBARA: Adam. Adam!

244
00:19:05,960 --> 00:19:07,188
Barbara!

245
00:19:07,520 --> 00:19:08,714
BARBARA: Adam!

246
00:19:10,000 --> 00:19:12,514
Adam, help. I'm getting all yellow!

247
00:19:13,720 --> 00:19:15,358
[Sandworm growls]

248
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:21,797
[Thunderous rumbling]

249
00:19:23,680 --> 00:19:25,193
[Barbara gasps]

250
00:19:27,640 --> 00:19:29,278
[Sandworm growls]

251
00:19:34,160 --> 00:19:35,798
[Sandworm whines]

252
00:19:39,240 --> 00:19:40,514
[Banging]

253
00:19:41,840 --> 00:19:43,193
[Sandworm roars]

254
00:19:49,040 --> 00:19:50,996
[Barbara sobs and gasps]

255
00:19:51,720 --> 00:19:54,553
We're trapped in this house
with those people.

256
00:19:59,400 --> 00:20:03,075
I can't believe we're eating Cantonese.
Is there no Szechwan up here?

257
00:20:03,160 --> 00:20:06,470
I plan to have a stroke from the amount
of MSG in this food.

258
00:20:06,720 --> 00:20:11,396
This is our first meal in this house,
so let's try to make it a pleasant one.

259
00:20:12,640 --> 00:20:14,631
CHARLES: Don't bait your mother.

260
00:20:14,800 --> 00:20:18,270
When we get settled, we'll build you
a darkroom in the basement.

261
00:20:18,640 --> 00:20:20,790
My whole life is a darkroom.

262
00:20:21,520 --> 00:20:23,192
One big dark room.

263
00:20:25,040 --> 00:20:29,591
You were miserable in New York City,
and you'll be miserable in the sticks.

264
00:20:29,720 --> 00:20:31,517
At least someone's life
hasn't been upheaved.

265
00:20:31,600 --> 00:20:36,037
I'm happy here. Those people in New York
don't know what they're missing.

266
00:20:40,280 --> 00:20:42,919
We could become
The Summer Art Center of New York.

267
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:45,753
I could start sculpting again.
I'm only truly happy when I'm sculpting.

268
00:20:45,840 --> 00:20:49,355
That's a very good idea.
That'll be very time-consuming.

269
00:20:49,480 --> 00:20:52,119
DELIA: First the house.
Otho and I have great plans.

270
00:20:52,200 --> 00:20:54,111
We should keep it the way it is.

271
00:20:54,200 --> 00:20:55,519
Good idea.

272
00:20:59,880 --> 00:21:03,714
CHARLES: The furniture truck is coming.
We must decide what goes and what stays.

273
00:21:03,800 --> 00:21:06,678
Everything goes,
along with whatever's in the attic.

274
00:21:12,040 --> 00:21:14,634
[Eerie instrumental music, background]

275
00:21:20,960 --> 00:21:23,269
[Crane hums, Otho shouts orders]

276
00:21:23,600 --> 00:21:24,828
Careful.

277
00:21:25,080 --> 00:21:28,675
Tell me what you do and I'll tell you
why my husband will fire you.

278
00:21:30,040 --> 00:21:32,508
- Isn't there an index?
- No, nothing.

279
00:21:34,680 --> 00:21:36,079
ADAM: What's this?

280
00:21:41,440 --> 00:21:44,557
DELIA: Do you know where that's going?
Did anyone tell you where...

281
00:21:44,640 --> 00:21:47,393
Why are there only three sculptures?
There were four sculptures.

282
00:21:47,480 --> 00:21:49,550
Where's the fourth sculpture?

283
00:21:49,640 --> 00:21:51,517
DELIA: [Shrieks] What are you doing?

284
00:21:51,600 --> 00:21:52,589
[Bang]

285
00:21:56,520 --> 00:21:59,717
ADAM: '"Betelgeuse, the bio-exorcist.
Troubled by the living?

286
00:21:59,800 --> 00:22:02,234
'"Is death a problem and not the solution?
Unhappy with eternity?

287
00:22:02,320 --> 00:22:05,357
'"Having difficulty adjusting?
Call Betelgeuse.'"

288
00:22:05,440 --> 00:22:06,589
[Bang]

289
00:22:08,600 --> 00:22:10,716
There's no number or instructions?

290
00:22:10,800 --> 00:22:13,553
Nothing. The '"bio-exorcist.'" I don't get it.

291
00:22:13,640 --> 00:22:14,789
[Bang]

292
00:22:18,040 --> 00:22:19,519
Straight back.

293
00:22:21,640 --> 00:22:24,518
Why don't you take a break
for half an hour?

294
00:22:31,160 --> 00:22:32,878
[Tap water running]

295
00:22:42,240 --> 00:22:43,434
[Smash]

296
00:22:44,520 --> 00:22:45,953
DELIA: Put that down!

297
00:22:46,040 --> 00:22:47,837
What the hell are you doing?

298
00:22:47,920 --> 00:22:50,036
DELIA: Listen to me!
CHARLES: Jesus!

299
00:22:51,320 --> 00:22:54,596
[Yells] Why are you doing this to me?
This is my art and it is dangerous.

300
00:22:54,680 --> 00:22:56,910
Do you think I want to die like this?

301
00:23:00,640 --> 00:23:03,279
[Eerie instrumental music, background]

302
00:23:08,320 --> 00:23:09,719
[Car horn honks]

303
00:23:10,840 --> 00:23:12,478
JANE: Hi. How are you?

304
00:23:21,080 --> 00:23:23,036
That little girl saw us.

305
00:23:23,520 --> 00:23:25,829
- Nobody can see us.
- But she did.

306
00:23:28,280 --> 00:23:30,919
- What happened to the previous owners?
- They drowned.

307
00:23:31,000 --> 00:23:33,798
Yes, they were family. I was devastated.

308
00:23:33,920 --> 00:23:36,195
- Here, take that.
- Is this the key to the attic?

309
00:23:36,280 --> 00:23:40,193
That's a skeleton key that will open
any door. Give that to your father.

310
00:23:40,760 --> 00:23:44,230
You might mention I single-handedly
decorated that house.

311
00:23:44,320 --> 00:23:47,949
If he needs any advice in that arena
have him come see me.

312
00:23:57,520 --> 00:23:59,988
[Suspenseful instrumental beat,
background]

313
00:24:05,520 --> 00:24:06,714
[Creak]

314
00:24:07,680 --> 00:24:09,671
Don't worry. I locked the door.

315
00:24:12,040 --> 00:24:13,837
[Key rattles in lock]

316
00:24:19,520 --> 00:24:21,272
[Betelgeuse cackles]

317
00:24:26,680 --> 00:24:28,671
BETELGEUSE:
Having trouble with the living?

318
00:24:28,760 --> 00:24:30,796
Tired of having your home violated?

319
00:24:30,880 --> 00:24:32,711
Want to get rid of them
pesky living critters?

320
00:24:32,800 --> 00:24:36,588
Well, come on down and see me,
the afterlife's leading bio-exorcist.

321
00:24:36,680 --> 00:24:39,956
Yes, sirree! I want to tell you,
I'll do anything!

322
00:24:42,520 --> 00:24:46,433
I'll scare 'em real bad.
I'll do anything to get your business.

323
00:24:46,640 --> 00:24:49,279
Hell! I'll possess myself if I gotta!

324
00:24:49,720 --> 00:24:52,518
Yo! I got demons runnin' all through me.

325
00:24:53,120 --> 00:24:54,997
Come on down and see it.

326
00:24:55,080 --> 00:24:58,152
If you act now, you get a free
demon possession with every exorcism.

327
00:24:58,240 --> 00:25:00,117
You can't beat that, can you?

328
00:25:00,200 --> 00:25:04,876
Bring the little partners. We've got plenty
of snakes for them to play with.

329
00:25:05,440 --> 00:25:09,353
Say it once, say it twice,
third time's a charm. And remember...

330
00:25:09,440 --> 00:25:12,716
"'I'll eat anything you want me to eat.
Swallow anything you want me to swallow.

331
00:25:12,800 --> 00:25:15,314
"'So, come on down, I'll chew on the dog."'

332
00:25:20,560 --> 00:25:23,028
[Dramatic instrumental music, background]

333
00:25:36,640 --> 00:25:38,039
[Key clanks]

334
00:25:39,240 --> 00:25:40,639
[Adam sighs]

335
00:25:42,680 --> 00:25:46,832
We need some help. I read something
in this book about emergencies.

336
00:25:47,640 --> 00:25:50,757
Here it is.
'"In case of emergency, draw a door.'"

337
00:25:55,440 --> 00:25:59,638
BARBARA: '"Draw a door'"? I don't know
why we keep looking in that stupid book.

338
00:26:01,840 --> 00:26:04,354
Maybe we should try that Beetle guy.

339
00:26:06,880 --> 00:26:07,869
Oh.

340
00:26:19,200 --> 00:26:22,158
You didn't actually think
that would work, did you?

341
00:26:22,240 --> 00:26:23,309
Aha!

342
00:26:24,720 --> 00:26:26,392
'"Knock three times.'"

343
00:26:30,040 --> 00:26:32,474
[Eerie, mystical music, background]

344
00:26:35,240 --> 00:26:36,559
[Rumbling]

345
00:26:55,240 --> 00:26:58,038
[Dramatic instrumental music, background]

346
00:27:10,480 --> 00:27:12,152
[Charles whistles]

347
00:27:26,160 --> 00:27:27,513
CHARLES: Birdies!

348
00:27:34,040 --> 00:27:35,473
[Bird chirps]

349
00:27:35,840 --> 00:27:37,034
Get it!

350
00:27:37,640 --> 00:27:38,470
LYDIA: Dad?

351
00:27:38,560 --> 00:27:39,356
[Bang]

352
00:27:39,440 --> 00:27:42,352
- Can't you see I'm relaxing?
- I want to tell you what I saw.

353
00:27:42,440 --> 00:27:46,035
What is the point of my coming here
if you people won't let me relax?

354
00:27:46,120 --> 00:27:47,951
Pumpkin, sweetheart...

355
00:27:49,040 --> 00:27:50,917
...go help your mother.

356
00:27:51,000 --> 00:27:53,912
Maybe you can relax in a haunted house,
but I can't.

357
00:27:59,080 --> 00:28:00,798
Hmm, nice building.

358
00:28:00,920 --> 00:28:02,990
CHARLES: Bad roof. Good parking.

359
00:28:08,240 --> 00:28:10,515
[Eerie instrumental vibrations]

360
00:28:16,440 --> 00:28:17,839
[Barbara gasps]

361
00:28:20,240 --> 00:28:22,356
[Light, playful melody, background]

362
00:28:33,480 --> 00:28:35,391
- Adam?
- This way, honey.

363
00:28:47,240 --> 00:28:49,151
You don't have an appointment.

364
00:28:49,240 --> 00:28:51,356
- We didn't know how to make one.
- Appointment for what?

365
00:28:51,440 --> 00:28:53,351
RECEPTIONIST: What do you want?
BARBARA: Help?

366
00:28:53,440 --> 00:28:57,228
Already? Just bit the big one
two months ago and you want help.

367
00:28:57,320 --> 00:28:59,470
What does that have to do with anything?

368
00:28:59,560 --> 00:29:02,552
You'll use up all your help vouchers: D-90s.

369
00:29:03,280 --> 00:29:06,238
You spend 125 years on earth
in that house...

370
00:29:06,720 --> 00:29:10,838
...during which you get only three class-one
D-90 intercessions with Juno.

371
00:29:10,920 --> 00:29:13,718
You probably haven't read through
the manual completely yet.

372
00:29:13,800 --> 00:29:16,633
You'll have to wait if you don't have
an appointment.

373
00:29:16,720 --> 00:29:20,156
- An appointment with whom?
- For Juno, your caseworker.

374
00:29:24,080 --> 00:29:26,275
Number 54,000,601. Ferndock!

375
00:29:36,240 --> 00:29:37,719
[Door squeaks]

376
00:30:10,240 --> 00:30:12,549
[Light instrumental music, background]

377
00:30:30,440 --> 00:30:32,829
- Want a cigarette?
- No, thank you.

378
00:30:34,080 --> 00:30:36,275
I'm trying to cut down myself.

379
00:30:52,760 --> 00:30:55,513
Adam, is this what happens when you die?

380
00:30:56,240 --> 00:30:58,595
RECEPTIONIST: This is what happens
when you die.

381
00:30:58,680 --> 00:31:01,797
That is what happens when he dies.
And that is what happens when they die.

382
00:31:01,880 --> 00:31:04,792
It's all very personal.
I'll tell you something.

383
00:31:04,880 --> 00:31:08,873
If I knew then what I know now,
I wouldn't have had my little accident.

384
00:31:08,960 --> 00:31:10,552
[The dead laugh]

385
00:31:11,040 --> 00:31:12,234
[Bell chimes]

386
00:31:12,640 --> 00:31:14,119
[Door squeaks]

387
00:31:14,320 --> 00:31:16,151
Maitland. Party of two.

388
00:31:16,240 --> 00:31:18,708
Take the handbook
and go to the sixth door.

389
00:31:18,800 --> 00:31:20,870
Oh, we forgot our handbook.

390
00:31:22,760 --> 00:31:24,079
[The dead grunt]

391
00:31:25,040 --> 00:31:25,995
Come on.

392
00:31:31,600 --> 00:31:35,115
VOICE ON INTERCOM: All new arrivals,
report to waiting room number eight.

393
00:31:35,200 --> 00:31:37,111
[Ambient office sounds]

394
00:31:37,400 --> 00:31:39,994
Flight 409 is arriving at gate three.

395
00:31:41,080 --> 00:31:43,514
How do I look?
There are no mirrors on this side.

396
00:31:43,600 --> 00:31:45,397
- You look fine.
- Fine.

397
00:31:45,640 --> 00:31:47,949
Thanks. I've been feeling a little flat.

398
00:31:48,040 --> 00:31:49,314
[Cackling]

399
00:31:52,720 --> 00:31:56,508
VOICE ON INTERCOM: Will the Peterson
party report to door number nine.

400
00:31:57,200 --> 00:31:59,998
Peterson party, please report
to door number nine.

401
00:32:01,480 --> 00:32:04,472
All new arrivals,
report to waiting room number eight.

402
00:32:10,840 --> 00:32:13,308
BARBARA: 125 years. I can't believe this.

403
00:32:13,920 --> 00:32:16,070
I can't believe they didn't tell us.

404
00:32:18,840 --> 00:32:20,751
Oh, Adam, what is this?

405
00:32:22,240 --> 00:32:24,037
[Ghoulish whispering]

406
00:32:24,920 --> 00:32:27,070
That's the Lost Souls' Room.

407
00:32:27,720 --> 00:32:30,393
A room for ghosts
that have been exorcised.

408
00:32:31,480 --> 00:32:32,993
JANITOR: Poor devils.

409
00:32:33,080 --> 00:32:35,116
That's death for the dead.

410
00:32:36,280 --> 00:32:38,271
It's all in the handbook.

411
00:32:38,480 --> 00:32:39,879
Keep moving.

412
00:32:44,480 --> 00:32:45,595
ADAM: Five.

413
00:32:47,120 --> 00:32:49,031
This is the sixth door.

414
00:32:51,320 --> 00:32:53,276
[Eerie instrumental vibrations]

415
00:32:55,640 --> 00:32:58,996
ADAM: [Echoes] Boy, this place just gets
weirder and weirder.

416
00:33:04,720 --> 00:33:05,709
Barbara.

417
00:33:09,280 --> 00:33:10,633
We're home!

418
00:33:11,560 --> 00:33:14,518
Look at this place! Everything's different.

419
00:33:16,320 --> 00:33:18,390
BARBARA: All our furniture's gone.

420
00:33:18,960 --> 00:33:21,474
How long do you suppose
we were waiting there?

421
00:33:21,560 --> 00:33:22,993
Three months.

422
00:33:24,120 --> 00:33:26,998
I'd almost given up on you.
I was about to leave.

423
00:33:27,080 --> 00:33:29,036
I do have other clients.

424
00:33:29,560 --> 00:33:32,028
- Are you Juno, our caseworker?
- Yes.

425
00:33:32,120 --> 00:33:35,078
I evaluate individual cases and determine...

426
00:33:35,320 --> 00:33:38,312
...if help is needed, deserved and available.

427
00:33:38,520 --> 00:33:39,430
Are you available?

428
00:33:39,520 --> 00:33:40,509
No.

429
00:33:41,680 --> 00:33:44,399
JUNO: What's wrong?
BARBARA: We're very unhappy.

430
00:33:44,800 --> 00:33:47,109
What did you expect? You're dead!

431
00:33:47,200 --> 00:33:51,273
We want to get rid of the people here.
We worked hard on this house.

432
00:33:51,360 --> 00:33:54,238
We probably wouldn't mind sharing
the house with people who were...

433
00:33:54,320 --> 00:33:56,595
- More like you used to be.
- Yes.

434
00:33:56,760 --> 00:33:58,318
But these people!

435
00:34:00,280 --> 00:34:02,191
JUNO: Things seem quiet here.

436
00:34:03,280 --> 00:34:06,238
You should thank God
you didn't die in Italy.

437
00:34:06,680 --> 00:34:08,033
The Deetzes.

438
00:34:08,200 --> 00:34:11,192
- Have you been studying the manual?
- We tried.

439
00:34:12,120 --> 00:34:15,795
The intermediate interface chapter
on haunting says it all.

440
00:34:15,960 --> 00:34:18,793
Get them out yourselves! It's your house.

441
00:34:19,920 --> 00:34:22,559
JUNO: Haunted houses aren't easy
to come by.

442
00:34:22,640 --> 00:34:24,949
BARBARA: We don't quite get it.
JUNO: I heard.

443
00:34:25,040 --> 00:34:26,792
Tore your faces off.

444
00:34:26,960 --> 00:34:30,919
It's useless to pull off your heads
in front of people who can't see you.

445
00:34:31,000 --> 00:34:33,309
- We should start simply?
- Start simply.

446
00:34:33,400 --> 00:34:36,198
Do what you know.
Use your talents. Practice.

447
00:34:37,920 --> 00:34:41,549
JUNO: You should have been studying
those lessons since day one.

448
00:34:42,320 --> 00:34:43,514
[Pager beeps]

449
00:34:43,600 --> 00:34:45,113
I've got to go.

450
00:34:45,240 --> 00:34:47,629
What about that guy in the flyer, Betel...

451
00:34:48,880 --> 00:34:52,031
Don't even say his name.
You don't want his help.

452
00:34:53,120 --> 00:34:53,996
We might.

453
00:34:54,080 --> 00:34:57,231
No, you don't.
He does not work well with others.

454
00:34:58,720 --> 00:35:00,358
What do you mean?

455
00:35:04,360 --> 00:35:06,237
I didn't want to bring it up.

456
00:35:06,320 --> 00:35:10,108
But rather than have you make
another mistake, I'll tell you.

457
00:35:11,280 --> 00:35:13,032
He was my assistant.

458
00:35:13,440 --> 00:35:16,477
But he was a troublemaker.
He went out on his own...

459
00:35:16,560 --> 00:35:18,835
...as a freelance bio-exorcist.

460
00:35:19,800 --> 00:35:23,588
Claimed he could get rid of the living.
Got into more trouble.

461
00:35:27,400 --> 00:35:30,995
I believe he's been sleazing
around your cemetery lately.

462
00:35:32,880 --> 00:35:35,519
The only way he can be brought back...

463
00:35:35,680 --> 00:35:38,319
...is by calling his name three times.

464
00:35:39,280 --> 00:35:41,271
But I strongly suggest...

465
00:35:41,680 --> 00:35:44,399
...that you remove the Deetzes yourselves.

466
00:35:45,080 --> 00:35:46,399
How do we contact you...

467
00:35:46,480 --> 00:35:48,436
...if we need you again?

468
00:35:49,320 --> 00:35:50,639
[Rumbling]

469
00:35:57,840 --> 00:36:00,434
Oh, Adam, that guy's in our cemetery.

470
00:36:01,120 --> 00:36:04,590
She's right. We just keep this simple.
We can do this.

471
00:36:04,880 --> 00:36:07,394
[Fast-paced, eerie music, background]

472
00:36:10,640 --> 00:36:12,073
[Fly buzzing]

473
00:36:27,680 --> 00:36:29,671
BETELGEUSE: Hey, you, come here!

474
00:36:30,200 --> 00:36:31,394
Hungry?

475
00:36:32,120 --> 00:36:34,111
Come on. Hey, come here.

476
00:36:35,320 --> 00:36:38,153
I got something good for you.
Come on over.

477
00:36:38,240 --> 00:36:40,993
We'll have a little bite, something to nosh.

478
00:36:41,080 --> 00:36:42,308
[Betelgeuse cackles]

479
00:36:42,400 --> 00:36:45,119
BETELGEUSE: Come here!
FLY: [Screeches] Help me!

480
00:36:47,600 --> 00:36:48,510
[Belch]

481
00:36:48,760 --> 00:36:52,878
Maxie, haven't I always made you money?
That's the only real question.

482
00:36:52,960 --> 00:36:57,272
Nobody made me money like you.
You were a demon until your nerves went.

483
00:36:57,680 --> 00:36:59,318
MAXIE: It's just that...

484
00:36:59,920 --> 00:37:03,117
...Winter River, Connecticut is,
if you'll forgive me, nowhere.

485
00:37:03,200 --> 00:37:06,237
Why would I want to invest that kind
of money in an old building...

486
00:37:06,320 --> 00:37:07,719
MAXIE: Way the hell up there!

487
00:37:07,800 --> 00:37:09,836
It's not a building. That's the beauty.

488
00:37:09,920 --> 00:37:13,708
The people don't know the value of
their property. I can buy the whole town.

489
00:37:13,800 --> 00:37:16,553
Then we own a whole town
in the middle of nowhere.

490
00:37:17,000 --> 00:37:18,433
Come and see.

491
00:37:18,560 --> 00:37:20,232
CHARLES: And bring Sarah.

492
00:37:20,880 --> 00:37:24,395
All right, Charles.
It's just that I am kind of busy here.

493
00:37:24,480 --> 00:37:25,469
[Ghoulish moaning]

494
00:37:25,560 --> 00:37:26,993
